{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_anaconda_ver01/data/sn85053044/00517178123/1948091001/0713.xml":{"full_text":"Republican Event With Big Barbeque At City Memorial Park Next Monday Noon\nJBROWNINGjfIifk \u201cCHIEF\n\n\u201cFor what avail, the plow or sail, or land or life, if Freedom fail\u201d\nVolume XVIII\nDavis To Speak\nHere Monday;\nBarbeque Noon\nTom Davis, republican candi\ndate for U. S. Senator, will be in\nBrowning Monday on his state\nwide itinerary of the general\nelection campaign and will be the\nmain speaker on a program to be\ngiven at the City Memorial Park\nat noon.\n<;W\nArrangements for the event\nare in charge of a local group of\nGlacier County republicans.\nFollowing the program there\nwill be a barbeque. with every\none afforded their full delight of\nsandwiches and coffee.\nSenatorial Candidate Davis,\nconsidered one of the most out\nstanding citizens of Montana, a\nbrilliant lawyer and speaker, will\ngive an \u201coff-the-cuff\u201d talk on\npolitical issues of the day.\nCounty candidates of the re\npublican ticket will be introduced.\nIf plans are successful, the\nevent will be highlighted by\nparticipation of a group of Black\nfeet, attired in Tribal costume.\nSeattle Relatives\nOf Dr. Schaeffer\nHere Visiting\nR. A. Schaeffer and his mother.\nMrs. A. V. Schaeffer, of Seattle\nare here this week visiting at the\nDr. Claude Schaeffer home. Dr.\nSchaeffer is one of the sons of\nMrs. Schaeffer.\nAt present connected with the\nWashington State Liquor Board,\nthe visiting brother for years\nresided in southern Idaho, where\nhe was employed by the Idaho\nPower Company and Utah Power\nLight Company projects in\ntheir early s t a g e sos develop\nment.\nBoth Mr. Schaeffer and his\nmother are enjoying their local\nvisit, the Museum of the Plains\nIndian, of which Dr. Schaeffer is\ncurator, being a most interesting\nand appealing attraction lo them.\nThe condition of Claude Davis,\nwho is confined to the local hos\npital, is said to be serious. In\njured when a young man, a spin\nal affliction developed as to finally\nmecessitate hospitalization.\nMr. and Mrs. Charles 'Coulter\nspent the Labor Day holidays\nwith his brother, Earl, at Kim\nberly, Alberta.\nSlaugh Appreciative Of\nCooperation For\nJunior Fair\u2019s Success\nNow that our Junior Fair is\nover we have time time to con\nsider both the achievement and\nresuits.\nWe feel that now is a good\ntime to extend and acknowledge\nour appreciation for the assist\nance and help which has been\ngiven.\nThe Browning Fair board is to\nbe complimented on their untir\ning efforts in promoting this Jun\nior Fair. Tho Browning Lions\nClub assisted very materially, by\ntheir moral support and assist\nance in sponsoring the printing\nof our premium book.\nWe also wish to thank all the\nBrowning businessmen, who con\ntributed financial assistance and\nmoral support. In tact, there\nwere so many who assisted and\nhelptd in making a success of the\nfair that it would be impossible\nto name all of the different\ngroups.\nSo our thanks and apprecia\ntion are extended to all who\nhelped in making a success of\nthe fair.\nWe also wish to thank the\nBlackfeet Tribal Business Coun\ncil for their financial assistance,\nboth in cash and for the eight\nrepayment heifers for the heifer\nscrambles.\nWe wish to thank the follow\ning out-of-town businessmen,\nwho extended definite assistance\ntoward the fair;\nErnie White, for his campaign\ning for us and for his enthusiasm\nand pep. which assisted in bring\ning in the following contribu\ntions:\nH. L. Patterson, sls: O. R.\nPaeham, sls; R. A. Finley. $25:\nD. C. Coovcr, sls; J. C. Hilton.\nS2O; R. L. Waddell. $10; L A.\nSitzman, $25; O. B. Skogen, $25:\nMercer Sheep Co., Spokane, sls:\nM. F. Sewingel, sls; George Mc-\nCabe, sls.\nIn addition to solicitations from\nthe above members, Mr. White\ncontributed $25 in cash.\nIf present plans materialize,\nwe will have at least one new ex\nhibit building for next year. We\nalso hope to have both our pres\nent livestock barns remodeled\nand repaired. A better water\nand light system for all of our\nbuildings is also included in the\nj present plan.\nK. G. Slaugh. Agricultural Ex\ntension Agent, Indian Service,\nPays SIOO Fine\nFor Beaver Skins\nKaiispell\u2014H. M. Knowllon was\ndiscovered to have two beavers,\nshot illegally, in his possession.\nThe beavers cost him SSO apiece\nwhen he appeared injustice court\nbefore Judge Bill Martin and was j\nfined SIOO. Three game wardens j\nsigned the complaint.\nSurprise Brithdiy Party\nGiven For Mrs. Bernice Brandi\nA surprise birthday party was\ngiven for Mrs. Bernice Brandt\nLabor Day, with Mrs. Randy\nManuel, the honored guest\u2019s sis\nter-in-law, as hostess.\nBesides local relatives, other\nguests were Mrs. Juanita Steven\nson and her daughter, Suzanne,\nof Fairfield, and Mrs. Brandt's\nmother, Mrs. Jessica Manuel, of\nHollywood.\nBrowning, Glacier County, Montana, Friday, September 10, 1948\nImportant!\nMake Sure You Are\nRegistered for the\nGeneral Election.\nRegistration Closes\nNext Friday at\n5 d. m.\nWheelers Coming\nTo Park Home\nFor Fall Vacation\nFormer Senator Burton K.\nWheeler and Mrs. Wheeler are\narriving this week from Wash\nington, 13. C. to spend a two\nmonths vacation at their Lake\nMcDonald home in Glacier Na\ntional Park.\nNow in private legal practice in\nthe national capitol. he said while\nin Billings this week that he\nwould be little concerned with\niwlitics.\nHowever. Montana candidates\nare much concerned about li i in.\nTo some of them his political\nblessing is like the gentle d e w\nfrom heaven. Areal purebred\npolitician, the Ex-Senator\u2019s im\npulse to bless is not apt to remain\nina smouldering stage through\nthe general election.\nRandy Manuel, accompanied by\nFrances; Grifiin, returned from\nChicago' Monday' evening, where\nthey ha\u00abl transported a truckload\nof house hold goods from Brown\ning.\nPARK THEATRE\n2 SHOWS EVERY NIGHT\u20147 and 9P. M.\nKridav and Saturday, Sept. Id and 11\nDOUBLE BILL\nRory Calhoun and Rhonda Fleming in\n\u201cAdventure Island\"\nWm. Boyd and Andy Clyde in\n\u201cMarauders\u201d\nSunday and Monday, Sept. 12 and li!\nBarbara Stanwyck and David Niven in\n\u201cThe Other Love\u201d\nShorts Borrah Minivtch and his Harmonica School\nTuesday and Wednesday, Sept 14 and 15\nJoe E. Brown and Noreen Nash in\n\u201cTender Years\u201d\nShorts News\nThursday Only, Sept. 16\nDon Castle and Virginia Christine in\n\u201cInvisible Wall\u201d\n.Shorts Jungle Close up News\nPatrol Yost Gets\nHis Indian Spots\nIn Wrong Place\nHighway Patrolman Yost made\na grave mistake recently when\nhe turned in the name of James\nSpotted Bear to Judge Lukin on\na charge of reckless driving.\nIn taking down the violator\u2019s\nname he made a mistake. It\nshould have been Slotted Eagle,\nfor it was Eagle who appeared in\ncourt, paid a SIOO fine and had\nhis driver's license revoked for a\nyear.\nAnd now, Spotted Bear is vin\ndicated. He is innocent. Spotted\nEagle looms as the bird whose\nspots to Yost were those like a\nbear\u2019s.\nFollick Grill Temporarily Closed\nThe Follick Grill is temporarily\nclosed that the owners, Mr. and\nMrs. Fred Follick, may be avail\ned a short vacation. With long\nhours through the tourist season,\nIxith have taken advantage of\nthe present recession from the\npeak of business recently.\nAugusta Baumgartner,\nW. G. M., 0. E. S.\nOn Official Visit\nBrowning Chapter, Order of\nEastern Star, will have as official\nguest Monday Augusta Baum\ngartner of Ronan, Worthy Grand\nMartron of Montana.\nArrangements are being made\nfor a luncheon at the Glacier Park\nHotel at noon and a banquet at\nthe Masonic Hall in Browning\nthat evening.\nA business meeting will con\nclude the event.\nPerry Kennedy Visits\nPerry Kennerly, in t h e early\npart of his life a resident of\nBrowning, and for the last 36\nyears a resident of Washington,\nD. C.. visited local relatives last\nweek. His wife during his west\nern trip is visiting her relatives\nin Kentucky.\nKennerly suffered serious in\njuries in an automobile crash in\nNew York City a year or so ago\nand since then his health has not\nbeen as robust as it used to be.\nPresley La\u00dfreche\nCouple Pay Visit\nMr. and Mrs. Presley La\u00dfreche\nof Nespelen, Wash, visited this\nweek with his brother. George,\nand other relatives, beginning\ntheir return Tuesday morning.\nPresley is credit officer at the\nColville Indian Agency.\nBorn at Glacier Park, his early\nschooling began at Kaiispell. He j\nis a graduate of Cliemawa and;\nthe Salem Business College. Prior j\nto World W ar 2, he worked in 1\nthe Indian Affairs Bureau office]\nin Washington, I). C. and 1 at e ri\nat the Blackfeet Agency in\nI Browning under former Superin\ntendent Graves, now at the head\nI of the Colville Agency.\nIn the late war Presley served\nin the air cor p s at Hendricks\nField, Florida, for three years,\nwhere held a captain\u2019s commiss\nion. Prior to his present position\nhe was for a year field aid to the\nsuperintendent at Grande Ronde\nAgency in Washington.\nThis week\u2019s visit to this section\nis his first in 10 years. While\nGlacier National Park\u2019s beauty,\nj he noted, remains unchanged be\ncause it is a project of eternity,\nroads serving it are badly in need\nof repair.\nHis wife, a native of the deep\nsoutii. was seeing Montana for\nthe first time in the couple\u2019s visit\nthis week.\nBlackfeet Leave\nFor Hop Fields\nC I o s e to 100 Blackfeet men,\nwomen and children left for Yak\nima Valley hop fields last Sunday,\na large truck being here to trans\nport them to the scene of work.\nThe pickers will be employed\nby Bob Sandall, who has a large\nj acreage of hops ready for har\nvesting. He said that this year\nthere is an average crop as com\npared with last year\u2019s lesser one,i\nwhich was far short of average.\nPicking will continue for about\nthree weeks, he said, with a fine\nopportunity for pickers to make\nmoney.\nAdvertising Pays.\nNumber 27\nBig Group Of\nLettermen For\nFootball Team\nWith a host of returning letter\nmen who have gained a few well\nplaced pounds. Browning High is\nembarking on its second season\nof six man football under Coach\nDon Fox.\nReturning lettermen are Jim\nGross. Jack Wood, Ed Conway.\nJim Lahr, Eugene Kipp, Wayne\nRacine, Robert Powell. John\nPowell. Jimmy Powell. Bob Mad\nman, FIo y d Gervais. Wilbur\nKuk a, Harold Nation. Dennis\nHarris and su c h newcomers as\nJack Welch, the Kennerly twins,\nGordon and Delano Grayson,\nRonald Norman, Ken Conway.\nBill Devereaux, Frank Guardipee.\nKeith Guardipee and others who\nhave not yet reported. These\nI toys will see plenty of action be\ncause of the nature of six man\nfootball.\nSix man is a wide open game,\nbut football nevertheless. It calls\nfor good tackling, blocking and\nball packing.\nAmong the better prospects are\nJim Cross. hard runner and good\npasser; Bronco Ed Conway, pow\nerful inside runner: Jack Wood,\nclever quarter-back: Eugene\nKipp, pass snagging end; Jim\nLahr, hard hitting end; John\nPowell, a terror on defence and\nHarold Nation, a fast man on end\nruns.\nThere will be plenty of com\npetition for positions throughout\ntho season which promises to bi\ntonse.\nSchedules will lie drawn up\nSaturday, September 11, in Great\nFalls and the fireworks will be\ngin.\nThe field is in beautiful shape,\nthe lights are in and the boys are\nprimed for the fall spectacle.\nG. N. Ry. Train\nSchedule To 8e\nChanged Sept. 15\nWith the closing of Glacier\nPark Hotels on September 15.\ndiscontinuance and in other cases\nchanging of schedules of trains\nthat have been serving the trav\neling public during the tourist\nseason has been announced by\nthe Great Northern Ry. Co.\nTrains 42 and 48 will be dis\ncontinued between Shelby an d\nGlacier Park. There will be no\nchange in schedule south of Shel\nby.\nOriental trains J and 4 will dis\ncontinue regular stop at Glacier\nPark and Belton. Train 2 will\nstop at Browning, Glacier Park\nand Belton to pic k up revenue\npassengers for Spokane and west\nwhere it is scheduled to stop\nTrain 4 will stop at Belton,\nGlacier Park and Browning to\ndischarge revenue passengers\nfrom Spokane and west.\nPoints south of Shelby will be\nincluded in the scheduled stops.\nFiandreau Students Leave\nForty-six students from\nthnughout the Blackfeet Reserva\ntion left yesterday for Fiandreau\nby school buses to begin the new\nterm, which begins next Monday.","height":"20500","width":"14688"}}
